Eddie Module on Stream discharge excel based data

Excel based analysis of discharge and urbanization

This uses the excel based data for the analysis of the effects of urbanization

Install libraries

The libraries need to be installed only one time and then loaded each time the script is opened and run.

# https://github.com/USGS-R/dataRetrieval

# general R packages to install if you dont have them
# remove the "#" if you need to run the installations

Load Libraires

Load the libraries each time you run the script.

# load these every time  
library(tidyverse)
library(scales)
library(lubridate)
library(janitor)
library(readxl)
library(skimr)
library(plotly)
library(patchwork)

# # load the USGS package
# library(dataRetrieval)

USGS Sites

These are the sites that are used in the data analysis below. The data can be downloaded again and then used for the analsyses.

USGS 12120000 MERCER CREEK NEAR BELLEVUE, WA
https://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/inventory/?site_no=12120000

USGS 12113000, Green River near Auburn, Washington
https://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/inventory/?site_no=12113000

USGS 12108500, Newaukum Creek near Black Diamond, Washington
https://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/inventory/?site_no=12108500

Read in Excel Files

This reads in the files into 3 separate dataframes that appear in the Environment tab in the upper right.


# This reads in the Green River data
green.df <- read_excel("../data/Green R.xlsx",
                 guess_max = 10000) %>% 
  mutate(site="Green") # adds Green to site name

# Read in Mercer Cr data
mercer.df <- read_excel("../data/Mercer Cr.xlsx",
                 guess_max = 10000) %>% 
  mutate(site="Mercer") # adds Mercer to site name


# read in the Newaukum data
new.df <- read_excel("../data/Newaukum Cr.xlsx",
                 guess_max = 10000) %>% 
  mutate(site="Newaukum") # adds Newaukum to site name

Combine all data frames

This will merge all the data files in a linear manner. The bind_rows command is nicer than the base R vesion as it will add all the data and if there are missing values in one dataframe it will still perform the merge.

streams.df <- bind_rows(green.df, mercer.df, new.df)

Graph of yearly peak discharge

This graphs the discharge data from each stream. This is the max flow that occured each year. If the name of a variable is put inside of the aes( here ) statment it will map the values of that vaiable to the type of symbol or color you have designated. These commands may be: aes(x = x_variable, y = y_variable, *color* = variable name of sites)
aes(x = x_variable, y = y_variable, *fill* = variable name of sites)
aes(x = x_variable, y = y_variable, *shape* = variable name of sites)
aes(x = x_variable, y = y_variable, *line_type* = variable name of sites)

This is the graph using the commands above and you can try changing these around 

streams.df %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y=discharge_cfs, color=site)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point()

Look at the highest discharge on record

rr streams.df %>% group_by(site) %>% filter( discharge_cfs == max(discharge_cfs, na.rm=TRUE))

Discharge Statistics

rr streams.df %>% group_by(site) %>% summarize( number = sum(!is.na(discharge_cfs)), mean_discharge_csf = mean(discharge_cfs, na.rm=TRUE), std_dev_discharge_csf = sd(discharge_cfs, na.rm=TRUE), stderr = sd(discharge_cfs, na.rm=TRUE)/sqrt(sum(!is.na(discharge_cfs))) )

Calculating probability

rr floodprob.df <- streams.df %>% group_by(site) %>% arrange(site, desc(discharge_cfs))%>% mutate(rank = 1:n()) %>% mutate(prob = rank / (n()+1)) %>% mutate(pct_prob = prob * 100) %>% mutate(recurrence = 1/prob)

Recurrance interval plot

rr floodprob.df %>% ggplot(aes(x = recurrence, y=discharge_cfs, color=site)) + geom_point() + scale_y_continuous(labels= comma )

Log Recurrance interval plot

rr floodprob.df %>% group_by(site) %>% ggplot(aes(x = log10(recurrence), y=log10(discharge_cfs), color=site)) + geom_point()

Look at Mercer Creek Before and after 1977

rr mercer_urban.df <- mercer.df %>% mutate(year = year(date)) %>% mutate(pre_post = case_when( year <= 1977 ~ _1977, year > 1977 ~ _1977
))

Calculating probability Mercer Cr Pre Post 1977

rr mercer_urban.df <- mercer_urban.df %>% group_by(pre_post) %>% arrange(desc(discharge_cfs))%>% mutate(rank = 1:n()) %>% mutate(prob = rank / (n()+1)) %>% mutate(pct_prob = prob * 100) %>% mutate(recurrence = 1/prob)

Mercer Creek pre post recurrece interval plot

rr mercer_urban.df %>% ggplot(aes(x = recurrence, y=discharge_cfs, color=pre_post)) + geom_point() + scale_y_continuous(labels = comma )

Green River Dam Effects

rr green_dam.df <- green.df %>% mutate(year = year(date)) %>% mutate(pre_post = case_when( year <= 1961 ~ _1961, year > 1961 ~ _1961
))

Calculating probability Green R Pre Post 1961

rr green_dam.df <- green_dam.df %>% group_by(pre_post) %>% arrange(desc(discharge_cfs))%>% mutate(rank = 1:n()) %>% mutate(prob = rank / (n()+1)) %>% mutate(pct_prob = prob * 100) %>% mutate(recurrence = 1/prob)

Green R pre post recurrece interval plot

rr green_dam.df %>% ggplot(aes(x = recurrence, y=discharge_cfs, color=pre_post)) + geom_point() + scale_y_continuous(labels = comma )

New R River Dam Effects

rr new_dummy.df <- new.df %>% mutate(year = year(date)) %>% mutate(pre_post = case_when( year <= 1977 ~ _1977, year > 1977 ~ _1977
))

Calculating probability Green R Pre Post 1961

rr new_dummy.df <- new_dummy.df %>% group_by(pre_post) %>% arrange(desc(discharge_cfs))%>% mutate(rank = 1:n()) %>% mutate(prob = rank / (n()+1)) %>% mutate(pct_prob = prob * 100) %>% mutate(recurrence = 1/prob)

Mercer Creek pre post recurrece interval plot

rr new_dummy.df %>% ggplot(aes(x = recurrence, y=discharge_cfs, color=pre_post)) + geom_point() + scale_y_continuous(labels = comma )
